# Day 20 – Phase 1 Complete: Looking Back Before Moving Forward | 100 Days of GRC
*By Ibrahim Abdullahi | 100-Day GRC Challenge: Securing OpenMRS on AWS*

---

## Twenty Days In

I started this challenge not really knowing what GRC meant in practice. I had heard the acronym. I knew it had something to do with security and compliance. But the actual substance — how the three pillars connect, what the frameworks look like, how compliance differs from security, what it means to assess and treat risk — that was largely new territory.

Twenty days later, I want to take stock honestly. What have I actually learned? Where do I still have gaps? And what does Phase 2 need to accomplish to take this from conceptual understanding to practical skill?

This entry is my attempt to answer those questions — not as a polished summary, but as a genuine reflection on where I am.

---

## What Phase 1 Actually Covered

Looking back at Days 1 through 19, the learning fell into roughly five areas:

**The GRC Foundation (Days 1–5)**
The first week was about understanding what governance, risk, and compliance each mean individually and how they function as an integrated system. The most important insight from this week was that GRC is not three separate departments doing three separate jobs — it is one discipline with three dimensions, and the three dimensions only work properly when they reinforce each other. A governance decision about encryption simultaneously addresses a risk and satisfies a compliance requirement. That integration is what makes GRC programs effective rather than bureaucratic.

**Frameworks and Regulations (Days 6–10)**
The second area covered the major frameworks and regulations I will be working with throughout this project. NIST RMF gave me a structured, seven-step process for managing risk across a system's lifecycle. HIPAA gave me the specific legal requirements for protecting patient health information. ISO 27001 showed me what a risk-based management system looks like when it is built to evolve continuously rather than just pass a one-time audit. PCI DSS illustrated what highly prescriptive compliance looks like and what its limitations are. And Day 10 grounded all of it in the patient safety reality that makes healthcare GRC different from any other sector.

**People and Documents (Days 11–12)**
Two days that I think are underrated in importance. Understanding who is responsible for GRC — the CISO, Risk Manager, Compliance Officer, System Owner, and Authorizing Official — matters because frameworks and policies do not implement themselves. People do. And the governance document hierarchy — policy, standard, procedure — matters because the distance between intent and action is often a missing or poorly written document. The Advocate Medical Group breach on Day 12 was a perfect illustration of what happens when that hierarchy is incomplete.

**Risk Assessment and Treatment (Days 13–14)**
These two days were where GRC started to feel the most practical and analytical. Building the risk picture for OpenMRS — identifying assets, threats, vulnerabilities, likelihood, and impact — gave me a structured way to think about security that goes beyond intuition. And working through the four treatment options — mitigate, transfer, accept, avoid — made clear that risk management is about making deliberate, documented decisions rather than just fixing things as they break. The Premera Blue Cross case on Day 14 was a sharp reminder of what implicit, undocumented risk "acceptance" actually costs.

**Compliance, Cloud, and Architecture (Days 15–18)**
The final stretch of Phase 1 brought the compliance-security distinction into focus, established the AWS shared responsibility model as the operating framework for this project, mapped the technical architecture of OpenMRS on AWS, and worked through the specific compliance and security controls required to handle ePHI in the cloud responsibly. By Day 18 I had a practical checklist of controls — encryption, IAM, CloudTrail, VPC configuration, BAA — that translates the conceptual GRC learning into specific technical requirements.

