## What Actually Surprised Me

Three things genuinely surprised me over the past twenty days:

**How often the same principles appear across different frameworks.** NIST RMF, HIPAA, ISO 27001, PCI DSS — they use different language and different structures, but they keep arriving at the same underlying requirements. Encrypt sensitive data. Control who has access. Monitor what is happening. Keep systems patched. Train people. Document your decisions. I expected the frameworks to be more different from each other. Instead they feel like different expressions of the same core discipline.

**How much of security is a governance and culture problem rather than a technical one.** I came into this challenge expecting to learn mostly about technical controls. What I found instead is that the most common cause of security failures is not technical sophistication — it is organizational behavior. Leaders who deprioritize risk. Documentation that is never maintained. Controls that exist on paper but are never verified. Training that gets clicked through without engagement. The technical solutions for most security problems are well understood. Getting organizations to actually implement and maintain them consistently is the harder challenge.

**How personal the healthcare context makes everything.** I noted this on Day 10 and it has stayed with me. The Düsseldorf hospital incident, the ransomware attacks that force staff to use paper records, the breaches that expose people's most sensitive health information — these are not abstract security failures. They affect real people at vulnerable moments in their lives. That context changes how I think about the work. It is not just an interesting technical and organizational challenge. It is work that matters.

