## A Real-World Anchor for the Phase 1 Lessons

Looking back across the breach cases I studied in Phase 1 — HCA Healthcare, Target, Anthem, Equifax, Community Health Systems, Premera, Excellus, Capital One, Scripps Health — a consistent pattern emerges that I want to carry forward into Phase 2.

In almost every case, the breach was not caused by an attack that no one could have anticipated or defended against. It was caused by known vulnerabilities that were not addressed, controls that existed on paper but were not functioning, monitoring that detected anomalies but did not trigger a response, or governance failures that meant no one had clear ownership of the problem.

The **2021 Florida water treatment facility attack** — while not a healthcare case — captures this pattern clearly. An attacker remotely accessed the facility's industrial control system and attempted to increase sodium hydroxide levels to dangerous concentrations. The attack was caught by an alert operator who noticed the mouse cursor moving on their screen. The defense was not a sophisticated security control. It was a human paying attention.

That case is a reminder that GRC is not just about building the right technical architecture. It is about building an organization where people are paying attention, where responsibilities are clear, where anomalies get investigated, and where the gap between policy and practice is continuously being narrowed. That is what Phase 2 is about.

